ğŸŸ© 1. Module: extract/csv_reader.py

âœ”ï¸ Purpose: Read raw customer data from a .csv file

Sample Input (data/customers.csv):

id,name,email
101, John Doe ,john@example.com
102, Jane Smith,invalid-email
103, ,noemail@example.com

Expected Output (Python list of dicts):

[
  {"id": "101", "name": " John Doe ", "email": "john@example.com"},
  {"id": "102", "name": "Jane Smith", "email": "invalid-email"},
  {"id": "103", "name": "", "email": "noemail@example.com"}
]



---

ğŸŸ¨ 2. Module: transform/clean_email.py

âœ”ï¸ Purpose: Remove records with invalid emails (no "@" or ".com")

Input:

[
  {"id": "101", "name": " John Doe ", "email": "john@example.com"},
  {"id": "102", "name": "Jane Smith", "email": "invalid-email"},
  {"id": "103", "name": "", "email": "noemail@example.com"}
]

Expected Output:

[
  {"id": "101", "name": " John Doe ", "email": "john@example.com"},
  {"id": "103", "name": "", "email": "noemail@example.com"}
]



---

ğŸŸ¨ 3. Module: transform/strip_fields.py

âœ”ï¸ Purpose: Strip whitespace from name field

Input:

[
  {"id": "101", "name": " John Doe ", "email": "john@example.com"},
  {"id": "103", "name": "", "email": "noemail@example.com"}
]

Expected Output:

[
  {"id": "101", "name": "John Doe", "email": "john@example.com"},
  {"id": "103", "name": "", "email": "noemail@example.com"}
]



---

ğŸŸ¥ 4. Module: load/json_writer.py

âœ”ï¸ Purpose: Save final cleaned list of dictionaries to a .json file

Expected Output (output/cleaned_customers.json):

[
  {"id": "101", "name": "John Doe", "email": "john@example.com"},
  {"id": "103", "name": "", "email": "noemail@example.com"}
]



